# Trivy ignore file. Each entry is one CVE/GHSA id followed by an
# optional `exp:YYYY-MM-DD` expiry. Trivy treats the file as
# authoritative; any id listed here is silently dropped from the
# scan output. Document the rationale here so re-evaluation has the
# context next time a maintainer reads it.
#
# Format reference: https://aquasecurity.github.io/trivy/latest/docs/configuration/filtering/#by-finding-ids
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# CVE-2026-40217 — LiteLLM "Arbitrary Code Execution via bytecode
# rewriting" (HIGH). Fixed in litellm 1.83.10.
#
# Rationale (mirrors the pyproject.toml comment on the litellm pin):
# the vulnerable surface is the LiteLLM proxy server's authenticated
# `/guardrails/test_custom_code` endpoint, per the x41-dsec advisory
# at https://www.x41-dsec.de/lab/advisories/x41-2026-001-litellm/.
# SACP consumes LiteLLM as an SDK only from `src/api_bridge/litellm/`
# and never binds the proxy or any /guardrails/* endpoints. The
# Python 3.14 pin (Constitution §6.8) prevents bumping to 1.83.10
# because litellm dropped Python 3.14 support in 1.83.8. Re-evaluate
# when (a) upstream issues a Python 3.14-compatible patch line, or
# (b) Constitution §6.8 is amended to allow Python 3.13.
CVE-2026-40217
